   <p>Knowing when to stop is proper troubleshooting.</p>
 
   <h2>Clinical Use Tip</h2>
   <p>Do not troubleshoot the battery while the monitor is connected to a patient. If monitoring is required, move the patient to a unit with verified power and battery function first.</p>
 
   <h2>Work Order Documentation (CCR Method)</h2>
   <p><strong>CCR = Complaint, Cause, Resolution</strong></p>
 
   <h4>Complaint</h4>
   <p>What was reported by the clinical staff.</p>
   <p><em>Example:</em><br>
   “Monitor battery fails to hold charge and shows error.”</p>
 
   <h4>Cause</h4>
   <p>What was observed during troubleshooting.</p>
   <p><em>Example:</em><br>
   “Battery seated properly but monitor does not recognize it; AC power confirmed good; spare battery tested with same results.”</p>
 
   <h4>Resolution</h4>
   <p>What action was taken.</p>
   <p><em>Examples:</em><br>
   “Monitor removed from service, labeled Out of Service, sent to Philips service for evaluation.”</p>
 
   <h2>Helpful Details to Include</h2>
   <ul>
-    <li>Outlet tested: ✅/❌</li>
-    <li>Power cord inspected: ✅/❌</li>
+    <li>Outlet tested: Yes/No</li>
+    <li>Power cord inspected: Yes/No</li>
     <li>Indicator lights or error codes: Record exact messages</li>
-    <li>External battery tested: ✅/❌</li>
+    <li>External battery tested: Yes/No</li>
     <li>Final device status: Out of Service</li>
   </ul>
 
   <h2>Final Thought</h2>
   <p>Patient safety comes first. Troubleshooting battery issues should always begin with external checks before assuming internal failure. Document all findings carefully and escalate appropriately. Correct labeling and removal from service prevent patient harm and ensure proper repair.</p>
   <p><strong>That is successful troubleshooting.</strong></p>
 
